def bubble_sort(numbers):
    # Length of the list
    n = len(numbers)

    # Traverse through all elements in the list
    for i in range(n):

        # Last i elements are already sorted, so inner loop will go until n-i-1
        for j in range(0, n - i - 1):

            # Swap if current element is greater than next one
            if numbers[j] > numbers[j + 1]:
                numbers[j], numbers[j + 1] = numbers[j + 1], numbers[j]

    return numbers

Here is a simple Java program that simulates a vending machine:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class VendingMachine {
    private static final double[] PRICES = {1.00, 2.50, 0.75, 3.00, 1.25};
    private static final String[] PRODUCTS = {"Coke", "Chips", "Water", "Snickers", "Gum"};

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Welcome to the Vending Machine!");
        while (true) {
            for (int i = 0; i < PRODUCTS.length; i++) {
                System.out.printf("%d. %s ($%.2f)\n", i + 1, PRODUCTS[i], PRICES[i]);
            }
            System.out.print("Please select a product or press 0 to exit: ");
            int choice = scanner.nextInt();
            if (choice == 0) {
                break;
            } else if (choice > 0 && choice <= PRODUCTS.length) {
                System.out.printf("You selected %s which costs $%.2f.\n", PRODUCTS[choice - 1], PRICES[choice - 1]);
                System.out.print("Please insert your money: ");
                double payment = scanner.nextDouble();
                while (payment < PRICES[choice - 1]) {
                    System.out.printf("Insufficient funds. Please insert at least $%.2f more: ", PRICES[choice - 1] - payment);
                    payment += scanner.nextDouble();
                }
                double change = payment - PRICES[choice - 1];
                if (change > 0) {
                    System.out.printf("Thank you! Your change is $%.2f.\n\n", change);
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Thank you! You have no change.\n");
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("Invalid selection. Please try again.");
            }
        }
        System.out.println("Thank you for using our Vending Machine!");
        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

This program first displays all available products with their prices and asks the user to make a selection. If the user chooses an invalid option, they are asked to try again. If they choose a valid product, they are then prompted to insert money. If the inserted amount is less than the price of the product, they are asked to insert more until the total is sufficient. If the total inserted amount is greater than the price, the remaining change is calculated and returned to the user. The process repeats until the user decides to exit by pressing 0.

